By Joanne Lipman
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 01/28/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> SACHY IPG OGIL
MARKETING, ADVERTISING (MKT)
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF) </IN>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Army, breaking off a 19-year-old relationship with its advertising agency, N.W. Ayer Inc., awarded a $100 million advertising contract to Young &amp; Rubicam Inc. 

   Ayer said it will take "appropriate legal action" against the Army "to recover from the damage unjustly inflicted on this company and its reputation." 

   The Army had decided in October that it wouldn't extend Ayer's contract, and opened its advertising to competitve bidding. 
In November, Ayer was suspended from bidding on U.S. government contracts because of alleged improprieties by a former employee. 
